observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the Municipal Accountant:
send confirmation letters to the National Government Agencies which usually transfer funds to the LGU in order to verify if the LGU still have unliquidated fund transfers in previous years;
if in the negative, gather accounting and treasury records that will prove that the unaccounted/dormant balances of fund transfers had been dormant for ten (10) years or more;
proceed with the process of filing a request for write-off in accordance with the specific guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 as amended by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; and
in the event that the required documents for the write-off cannot be completed or obtained such that the dormant amounts will not qualify for write-off, prepare the Disbursement Voucher for the return to the Bureau of Treasury the unaccounted/dormant balances in the Due to NGAs account amounting to ₱29,205,582.70 to extinguish the liability of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Health Officer:

Obtain from the DOH Eastern Visayas Center of Health Development the actual information on the unit cost and quantities of the vaccines received by the LGU in relation to its vaccination program;


We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant record using the perpetual inventory system, the vaccines received by the LGU and the doses dispensed, using as reference the report/documents submitted by the MHO.

We recommended that the offices concerned be directed to:
Provide in the Annual Investment Plan sufficient details of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to be funded out of the DF;
Expedite the implementation of development projects so that more desired benefits could be enjoyed by the constituents as early as possible;
Review unimplemented PPAs to ascertain viability of their implementation for the ensuing year, otherwise, reprogram for a more viable and significant PPAs in accordance to the socio-economic development and environmental management requirements.

We recommended that the:
Municipality update its Local Revenue Code;
Accounting and Budget Office coordinate in the treatment of various revenue accounts and preparation of reports;
Local Finance Committee propose a reasonable income to be collected for the ensuing year, taking into account prior years’ experience as aide in setting the targets; and
Conduct periodic review of collection performance and implement corrective measures to fully attain projections during the year.
